Sure, there are several React Material UI datepickers that support selecting multiple dates. Here are a few options:

1. Material UI DatePicker: This is a built-in date picker component in Material UI that allows users to select a single date. However, you can use the `Multiple` prop to enable selecting multiple dates.
```
import { DatePicker } from '@material-ui/core';
function MyComponent() {
  const [selectedDates, setSelectedDates] = useState([]);
  const handleDateChange = (date) => {
    setSelectedDates((prevDates) => [...prevDates, date]);
  };
  return (
    <DatePicker
      value={selectedDates}
      onChange={handleDateChange}
      Multiple
    />
  );
}
```
2. React Material UI DateRangePicker: This component allows users to select a range of dates, rather than a single date. However, you can use the `Multiple` prop to enable selecting multiple ranges of dates.
```
import { DateRangePicker } from '@material-ui/core';
function MyComponent() {
  const [selectedRanges, setSelectedRanges] = useState([]);
  const handleDateRangeChange = (range) => {
    setSelectedRanges((prevRanges) => [...prevRanges, range]);
  };
  return (
    <DateRangePicker
      value={selectedRanges}
      onChange={handleDateRangeChange}
      Multiple
    />
  );
}
```
3. Material UI DateRangeController: This component is a more advanced date picker that allows users to select a range of dates, as well as a specific date within that range. It also supports selecting multiple ranges of dates.
```
import { DateRangeController } from '@material-ui/core';
function MyComponent() {
  const [selectedRanges, setSelectedRanges] = useState([]);
