  };
  return (
    <DateRangeController
      value={selectedRanges}
      onChange={handleDateRangeChange}
      Multiple
    />
  );
}
```
All of these options provide a Material UI-style date picker experience and support selecting multiple dates. You can choose the one that best fits your needs and requirements.

Sure, I can guide you on how to create a date picker in React using Material UI that supports the selection of multiple dates. However, please note that the Material UI DatePicker does not natively support multiple date selections. 

To achieve this, you would need to manage an array of selected dates in your state and create a custom function to handle date selection. Here's a basic example:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { DatePicker } from '@material-ui/pickers';

function MultiDatePicker() {
  const [selectedDates, setSelectedDates] = useState([]);

  const handleDateChange = (date) => {
    setSelectedDates((prevDates) => {
      const index = prevDates.findIndex((d) => d.isSame(date, 'day'));
      if (index === -1) {
        return [...prevDates, date];
      } else {
        return prevDates.filter((d) => !d.isSame(date, 'day'));
      }
    });
  };

  return (
    <DatePicker
      value={selectedDates}
      onChange={handleDateChange}
      renderDay={(date, selectedDate, isInCurrentMonth, dayComponent) => {
        const isSelected = selectedDates.find((d) => d.isSame(date, 'day'));
        return isSelected ? <div style={{ backgroundColor: 'blue' }}>{dayComponent}</div> : dayComponent;
      }}
    />
  );
}

export default MultiDatePicker;
```

In this example, `handleDateChange` checks if the selected date is already in the `selectedDates` array. If it is, it removes it; if it isn't, it adds it. The `renderDay` prop is used to customize the appearance of the selected dates.

Please remember to install the necessary dependencies by running `npm install @material-ui/pickers` and `npm install @date-io/date-fns` in your terminal.

