To create a React Material UI datepicker that supports selecting multiple dates, you can use the `DateRangePicker` component from the `material-ui-pickers` library. Here's an example:
```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import DateRangePicker from 'material-ui-pickers/DateRangePicker';

const MyComponent = () => {
  const [selectedDates, setSelectedDates] = useState([]);

  const handleDateChange = (value) => {
    setSelectedDates(value);
  };

  return (
    <DateRangePicker
      value={selectedDates}
      onChange={handleDateChange}
      selectionMode="multi"
      renderInput={({ input }) => (
        <div>
          <input {...input} />
          <span>Select dates</span>
        </div>
      )}
    />
  );
};
```
In this example, we use the `useState` hook to manage the state of the selected dates. The `handleDateChange` function updates the state with the selected dates.

The `DateRangePicker` component is used to render the datepicker. We pass the `value` and `onChange` props to the component, and set the `selectionMode` to `"multi"` to allow for multiple date selections.

The `renderInput` prop is used to customize the appearance of the input field.

You can use this component in your React app to allow users to select multiple dates.

React Material-UI doesn't have a built-in multiple date picker, but you can leverage the third-party `material-ui-pickers` library as a base and build a custom solution. First, you'll need to install the required dependencies:

```sh
npm install @material-ui/pickers @material-ui/core @date-io/dayjs
```

Here's a custom `MultipleDatePicker` component using `material-ui-pickers` for multiple date selection:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import {
  MuiPickersUtilsProvider,
  DatePicker as MaterialDatePicker,
} from '@material-ui/pickers';
import DayjsUtils from '@date-io/dayjs';

function MultipleDatePicker({ dates, onDatesChange }) {
  const [selectedDate, setSelectedDate] = useState(new Date());

  const handleDateChange = (date) => {
    setSelectedDate(date);

    if (!dates.some((selected) => selected.isSame(date, 'day'))) {
      onDatesChange([...dates, date]);
    } else {
      onDatesChange(dates.filter((selected) => !selected.isSame(date, 'day')));
    }
  };

  const handleRenderDay = (date, _, dayInSelectedMonth) => {
    const isSelected = date && dates.some((selected) => selected.isSame(date, 'day'));

    return (
      <span
        style={{
          fontWeight: isSelected ? 'bold' : undefined,
          color: isSelected ? 'red' : undefined,
        }}
      >
        {dayInSelectedMonth}
      </span>
    );
  };

  return (
    <MaterialDatePicker
      value={selectedDate}
      onChange={handleDateChange}
      renderDay={handleRenderDay}
    />
  );
}

const App = () => {
  const [dates, setDates] = useState([]);

  return (
    <MuiPickersUtilsProvider utils={DayjsUtils}>
      <MultipleDatePicker dates={dates} onDatesChange={setDates} />
    </MuiPickersUtilsProvider>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this example, the custom `MultipleDatePicker` component receives `dates` and `onDatesChange` props. The component uses Material-UI's DatePicker and adds a custom `renderDay` function that handles the multiple date selection feature. The highlighted dates will appear bolder and in red.

When you use this component, pass an array of dates as the `dates` prop, and a callback function to handle the date changes as `onDatesChange` prop.

You can further customize the styling and behavior to match your requirements.
